(- Architecture Context and Design Goals) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(PrivateTx v3 exists inside a mixed public/private UTXO environment. Public transactions keep the) Tj
T*
(conventional transparency properties, while private transactions introduce note commitments,) Tj
T*
(nullifiers, anchors, encrypted payloads, and block-level proof gates. Consensus validators) Tj
T*
(process both lanes under one acceptance path. The private lane is not an off-chain extension; it) Tj
T*
(is validated in-band with block acceptance and state transitions. That architecture decision is) Tj
T*
(what allows private features to be optional for users but non-optional for validators whenever) Tj
T*
(private activity is present[^2][^4].) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The design goals are practical and measurable. First, preserve deterministic validation under) Tj
T*
(adversarial input. Second, hide private transfer amounts and recipient identity links on-chain) Tj
T*
(while preserving replay resistance. Third, ensure private-path failures fail closed and remain) Tj
T*
(diagnosable. Fourth, keep wallet recovery deterministic through seeded key derivation and) Tj
T*
(recipient bundle consistency checks. Fifth, keep production operations safe through pinned) Tj
T*
(binaries, bounded payloads, and explicit timeout constraints around proving/verifying pipelines.) Tj
T*
(These goals are technical constraints, not aspirational themes.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The end-to-end posture is shown below. The flowchart illustrates that private activity traverses) Tj
T*
(wallet construction, mempool policy checks, miner transformation, block proof gating, and final) Tj
T*
(consensus acceptance. Any hard failure at those gates is expected behavior. The architecture) Tj
T*
(intentionally prefers deterministic rejection over permissive acceptance because consensus) Tj
T*
(safety has higher priority than convenience in private-state handling.) Tj
T*
